<font color="#FF0000">TESTING FOR BIAS, AND MINDSET</font><br>
<tt>Tue Aug 19 19:24:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
This is a fascinating dialog, and I agree with much of what you say.  I have seen how impersonal an NVA rocket can be when it dead-centers a South Vietnamese home.  And I agree about the communists' degrading of the value of human life--I've also seen it.  <br><br>
Apparently, Carl Sagan is a sore point with you.  I am going to use one sentence from above to illustrate how I evaluate a statement for its bias and its context.  It is this one:<br><br>
&quot;Carl Sagan was a communist, The dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.&quot;<br><br>
I substitute the word &quot;communist&quot; for other words, and see if the sentence still makes sense.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was a writer; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was a scientist; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was an American; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was a Caucasian; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was a capitalist; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
--Carl Sagan was a thinker; the dehumanizing question Sagan posed therefore had no value.<br><br>
Each of these statements about Dr. Sagan was correct.  But the logic failed when placed in this context.  By the way, the success of his Cosmos series and the other books he has sold make a good case that Sagan was, indeed, a capitalist.<br><br>
I understand where you are coming from concerning communism as we saw it in SEA.  Nobody who values life can in good conscience support what has happened at communist hands in Vietnam, Laos, Combodia and other countries.<br><br>
But at the same time, we must be careful in our language and thinking to not endorse to same methods the communists used in SEA in our dealings with other peoples.  To be conservative, have good family values, endorse hard work, etc., doesn't necessarily mean one must also be racist in statements; that is my main point.  <br><br>
I understand fully, and endorse, your thoughts about the beauty of this world, the &quot;masterful design clearly visible in the universe,&quot; and the presence of a Supreme Being.  Vietnam is clearly one of the most beautiful places on earth (outside of Western Oregon, that is).  Those who were forced to leave must still grieve the loss.  <br><br>
Your last question, about what does it matter what you call a person you are going to kill, strikes to the heart of the my concerns.  The Native Americans respected their enemies, even in battle.  I think that by dehumanizing the Vietnamese, we to some extent lost sight of the fact that they were able to plan, organize, and put into effect complex strategies--in short, we underestimated their potential (at least at the very high levels of government).  <br><br>
We also overestimated our abilities.  We had technology, we had money, we had the best education of our Armed Forces.  How could they hold up against that?  <br><br>
Well, they did.  And I think that our mind-set had something to do with it.  <br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


